Graham began the [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season]] as a watch lists candidate for the [[Chuck Bednarik Award|Bednarik Award]], Hendricks Award, [[Lombardi Award]], [[Lott Trophy]], and [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy|Nagurski Trophy]] for the [[2009 Michigan Wolverines football team]].<ref name=BTFWRS72>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/big10/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/football-20090907.pdf|title=Big Ten Football Weekly Release September 7, 2009|accessdate=2009-10-01|date=2009-09-07|publisher=[[Big Ten Conference]]|page=6}}</ref> He was also selected by [[ESPN]] as the 10th best player in the Big Ten Conference before the season started.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/bigten/post/_/id/2196/ranking-the-big-ten-brandon-graham-no-10|title=Ranking the Big Ten: Brandon Graham, No. 10|accessdate=2009-11-17|date=2009-05-29|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|author=Rittenberg, Adam}}</ref> He concluded the season as the [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] recipient as the Big Ten co-MVP (with [[Daryll Clark]]). He was the seventh defensive player to earn the award and second in the last 25 years as well as the first co-recipient.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DTNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12C7E89DA99508E8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Kelly has conversation with Notre Dame|accessdate=2009-12-14|date=2009-12-09|page=2B|work=[[The Detroit News]]}}</ref> Graham was the first player from a losing team in eight years and only the second player to win who was not either [[Big Ten Conference football individual honors|Big Ten offensive or defensive player of the year]].<ref name=Dwtan>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12C7E43D6F34BF50&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Double winners twice as nice - Graham, Clark share honor as Big Ten's best |accessdate=2009-12-14|date=2009-12-09|page=1, Sports section|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Greenstein, Teddy}}</ref> He posted 26 TFLs in 12 games, which led the nation with 2.17 average tackles for a loss per game (ahead of conference rival [[O'Brien Schofield]] who was second with 1.884).<ref name=BSNPR>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/mfb/natlRank.jsp?year=2009&div=B&rpt=IA_playertacklesloss&site=org|title=Bowl Subdivision (FBS) National Player Report: Tackles for Loss: Year: 2009|accessdate=2010-01-08|date=2010-01-08|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]}}</ref><ref name=TAS09/> His total of 10.5 sacks ranked fourth in the Big Ten Conference.<ref name=TAS09>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-footbl/stats/2009-2010/confldrs.html|title=The Automated ScoreBook: 2009 Big Ten Conference Individual Statistics Through games of Jan 08, 2010|accessdate=2010-01-15|date=2010-01-08|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Four times during the season, he recorded multiple sack games and he had three solo TFLs in four games. He ended his career at Michigan with 9 TFLs (8 solo and 2 assists) in his final two games, including a career-high 5 solo TFLs against [[2009 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] in the 2009 [[Michigan <U+2013> Ohio State rivalry|rivalry game]], which was the final game of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/mfb/playerDetail.jsp?yr=2009&org=418&player=55|title=Team: Michigan: Year: 2009 Thru 11/21/09: Player: Brandon Graham|accessdate=2009-11-24|date=2009-11-21|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]}}</ref>  Graham was one of seven finalists for the Hendricks Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:MNAB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12C7D5F5D546EE10&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Michigan's Graham a finalist for Hendricks Award |accessdate=2009-12-14|date=2009-12-03|page=2B|work=[[Manistee News Advocate]]}}</ref> At the conclusion of the season he was a 2009 First-team All-Big Ten selection by the coaches and media.<ref name=BTA2FACTaIH9>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/112309aag.html|title=Big Ten Announces 2009 Football All-Conference Teams and Individual Honors|accessdate=2009-11-24|date=2009-11-23|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> He was a First-team [[2009 College Football All-America Team]] selection by [[ESPN]], [[Rivals.com]] and [[Scout.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=4826163|title=ESPN.com All-America Team (video)|accessdate=2010-01-14|date=2010-01-14|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|author=Maisel, Ivan}}</ref><ref name=R2AAT>{{cite web|url=http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=1028724|title=Rivals.com 2009 All-America Teams|accessdate=2009-12-15|date=2009-12-15|publisher=[[Rivals.com]]}}</ref><ref name=SAAT>{{cite web|url=http://www.scout.com/2/928745.html|title=Scout.com All-America Team|accessdate=2009-12-15|date=2009-12-14|publisher=[[Scout.com]]|author=Safrit, Miller}}</ref> and he was a Second-team [[All-American]] defensive line selection by the [[Walter Camp Football Foundation]], [[Associated Press]], ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', ''[[College Football News]]'' and ''[[The Sporting News]]''.<ref name=2WSCAATA>{{cite web|url=http://waltercamp.org/index.php/news/2009_walter_camp_all_america_team_announced/|title=2009 Walter Camp All-America Team Announced|accessdate=2009-12-12|date=2009-12-10|publisher=[[Walter Camp Football Foundation]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/college-football/article/2009-12-15/2009-sporting-news-college-football-all-american-second-team|title=2009 Sporting News college football All-American second team|accessdate=2009-12-15|date=2009-12-15|work=[[Sporting News]]}}</ref><ref name=IMl6AAAA>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/college-football/article/2009-12-15/ingram-mcclain-lead-6-alabama-ap-all-americans|title=Ingram, McClain lead 6 Alabama AP All-Americans|accessdate=2009-12-15|date=2009-12-15|work=[[The Sporting News]]}}</ref><ref name=S2AA>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/ncaa/12/15/all-america/index.html|title=SI.com's 2009 All-Americas|accessdate=2009-12-15|date=2009-12-15|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref><ref name=2CAAD&ST>{{cite web|url=http://cfn.scout.com/2/929578.html|title=2009 CFN All-America Defense & Special Teams|accessdate=2009-12-16|date=2009-12-16|work=[[College Football News]]}}</ref>  He was an honorable mention All-American by ''[[Pro Football Weekly]]'' (which had no second team).<ref name=PFWloAiTaW>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/385/story/1643826.html|title=Pro Football Weekly's list of All-Americans includes Tigers and Wildcats|accessdate=2009-12-30|date=2009-12-21|work=[[The Kansas City Star]]|publisher=KansasCity.com|author=DeArmond, Mike}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Graham was again selected as the team MVP,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DTNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12C6427628080FE8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=U-M's Warren ponders declaring for NFL Draft|accessdate=2009-12-12|date=2009-12-04|work=[[The Detroit News]]|page=5B|author=Chengelis, Angelique S. }}</ref> which made him the school's first defensive player to be two-time MVP.<ref name=55BG/>  As of December 2009, Graham was the only Big Ten player on [[Mel Kiper]]'s "Big Board" Top 25.<ref name=Dwtan/> Brandon Graham earned MVP honors at the January 30, [[2010 Senior Bowl]] with five tackles, two sacks, one forced fumble.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/football/nfl/01/30/senior.bowl/|title=Graham shines at Senior Bowl|accessdate=2010-02-01|date=2010-01-30|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Pauline, Tony}}</ref>

